{
  "texts": [
    "By employing co-citation analysis, researchers can compare the frequency at which two publications have been referenced together (Small 1973; Üsdiken and Pasadeos 1995).",
    "The greater the number of times these publications have been co-cited, the higher the likelihood that they address similar subjects, enabling the identification of invisible colleges and the recognition of shared interests or objectives (Lievrouw 1989; Zupic and Čater 2015).",
    "Simultaneously, co-citation analysis unveils the foundation upon which the publications are being written (López-Cabarcos et al. 2020).",
    "Figure 3 displays the top ten references obtained from the reference co-citation analysis.",
    "The criterion for this analysis involved a minimum threshold of six cited references for inclusion, established according to citation counts."
  ]
}